      "\n  have h₁ : (u / v : 𝓞 K) = (u : 𝓞 K) / v := by simp [Units.ext_iff]\n  have h₂ : (u : K) / ((v : 𝓞 K) : K) = (u : K) / (v : K) := by simp [Units.ext_iff]\n  have h₃ : (u / u : (𝓞 K)ˣ) = (1 : (𝓞 K)ˣ) := by\n    simp [Units.ext_iff]\n  have h₄ : (u : K) / (u : K) = (1 : K) := by\n    haveI : DivInvMonoid K := by infer_instance\n    have h₄₁ : (u : K) ≠ 0 := by\n      intro h₄₁\n      have h₄₂ : (u : 𝓞 K) = 0 := by\n        norm_cast at h₄₁ ⊢\n        <;> simp_all [Units.ext_iff]\n      simp_all [Units.ext_iff]\n    field_simp [h₄₁]\n  simp_all [Units.ext_iff]\n  <;>\n  (try\n    norm_num) <;>\n  (try\n    simp_all [Units.ext_iff]) <;>\n  (try\n    field_simp [Units.ext_iff]) <;>\n  (try\n    ring_nf) <;>\n  (try\n    norm_num) <;>\n  (try\n    simp_all [Units.ext_iff]) <;>\n  (try\n    linarith)",
      "\n   - Alternatively, we can directly use `Units.div_def` which says `u / v = u * v⁻¹`, then coerce to `K`.\n3. Compute `(↑u : K) / (↑u : K)` when `u : (O K)ˣ`. Since `↑u ≠ 0`, `↑u / ↑u = 1`.\n4. Use this to prove that the RHS is `(↑u : K) / (↑v : K) + 1`, and since `(u / v : (O K)ˣ)` coerces to `(↑u : K) / (↑v : K)`, we get that both sides are equal.\n\nBut in Lean, there is actually a better way: The key is that `(↑(u / v) : K)` is the same as `(↑u : K) * (↑v : K)⁻¹`. \n\nBut also, in Lean, `(u : K) / (v : K)` is `(u : K) * (v : K)⁻¹ = (u : K) * (↑(v⁻¹) : K)`. But since `(↑(v⁻¹) : K) = (↑v : K)⁻¹`, these are equal. \n\nThus `(↑(u / v) : K)` = `(u : K) / (v : K)`. \n\nIn Lean, `(↑(u / v) : K)` is `(↑(u * v⁻¹) : K)` = `(↑u : K) * (↑v⁻¹ : K)` = `(↑u : K) * (↑v : K)⁻¹` = `(↑u : K) / (↑v : K)`.\n\nSimilarly, `(↑u : K) / (↑u : K)` is `1`.\n\n**Implementation in Lean:**\n\n1. Use `Units.ext_iff` to understand coercions and inverses.\n2. Note that for any unit `v`, `(↑v : K) ≠ 0`, so `↑v` is invertible in `K`.\n3. For `v : (O K)ˣ`, `↑v⁻¹ = (↑v)⁻¹`. \n   - Because `↑v * ↑v⁻¹ = 1`, so `↑v⁻¹ = (↑v)⁻¹`.\n   - In Lean, we can use the fact that coercion is multiplicative and `(v : M)⁻¹` for `v : Units M` is already defined as `v⁻¹`, and the coercion to `K` respects inverses (`(↑v⁻¹ : K) = (↑v : K)⁻¹`). \n   - Indeed, `Units.ext_iff` tells us how to compute `↑(v⁻¹)`.\n   - Alternatively, perhaps Lean has a coercion we can use directly like `Units.mapHom` or something.\n   - Actually, `Units.mapHom` could work: if we have `f : M → N` a monoid hom, then `f(v)⁻¹ = (v⁻¹)`, where `v : Units(M)` and `f(v) = (v : N)`. Here, `f : (O K)ˣ → Kˣ` is the coercion, and `f(v⁻¹) = (v⁻¹ : K)`.\n\nBut perhaps in Lean, `(↑v⁻¹ : K)` is not exactly `(↑v : K)⁻¹` automatically. \n\nBut for the coercion to `K`, we can note that in `K`, `(v : K) * (↑v⁻¹ : K)` = `↑v * ↑(v⁻¹)` = `↑(v * v⁻¹)` = `↑1` = `1`, hence `(v : K)⁻¹ = (v⁻¹ : K)`. \n\nAlternatively, use that `(a : K)⁻¹ = (a⁻¹ : K)` when `a : (O K)ˣ`.\n\nTherefore, we can write:\n`(u / v : (O K)ˣ) = (u * v⁻¹ : (O K)ˣ)`, so `(↑(u / v) : K)` = `(↑u * ↑v⁻¹ : K)` = `(↑u : K) * (↑v : K)⁻¹`.\n\nBut also `(u : K) / (v : K)` = `(↑u : K) * (↑v : K)⁻¹`, because division is multiplication by the inverse.\n\nThus `(↑(u / v) : K)` = `(u : K) / (v : K)`.\n\nSimilarly, `(u : K)/(u : K)` = 1 because `(u : K) ≠ 0`.\n\nBut we must ensure that in Lean, `(u : K) / (v : K)` is the same as `(u : K) * (v : K)⁻¹`. Indeed, in Lean, division is defined as `a / b = a * b⁻¹`, so we are good.\n\n**Verification of Coercion:**\n\nIn Lean, `(v : (O K)ˣ)` and `(v : K)` are different, because there is no coercion from `(O K)ˣ` to `K`; instead, there is a coercion from `(O K)` to `K`, and the group of units `(O K)ˣ` has an associated coercion to `(O K)`.\n\nBut in our statement, `(u : K)` is the same as `(↑u : K)`, because `u : (O K)ˣ` can be first coerced to `(O K)` (in the monoid of `O K`) and then to `K`, but since `↑` is multiplicative and `K` is a field, this is the same as `(u : (O K)) : K`.\n\nBut when you have `(u : (O K)ˣ)` and `v : (O K)ˣ`, and you write `(u / v : (O K)ˣ)`, it is `u * v⁻¹`. \n\nTo compute `(u / v : (O K)ˣ)` as an element of `K`, we have `(u : (O K)ˣ) : (O K)` (which is the same as `u : (O K)`), and then `(u : O K) : K` is `(u : K)`. \n\nBut `u / v : (O K)ˣ` is `u * v⁻¹`, and the coercion from `(O K)ˣ` to `(O K)` is the monoid hom sending `u : (O K)ˣ` to `(u : (O K))`. Then the coercion `(O K) → K` sends `(u : (O K))` to `(u : K)` and `(v⁻¹ : (O K))` to `(v⁻¹ : K)`. \n\nBut also, `u : (O K)ˣ` can be first coerced to `(O K)` then to `K`, and similarly for `v`, and then multiplication and inversion are as in `K`.\n\nAlternatively, note that:\n\n`↑(u / v : (O K)ˣ)` in `K` is `(↑(u / v) : K)` = `(↑(u * v⁻¹) : K)` = `(↑u : K) * (↑(v⁻¹ : (O K)ˣ) : K)` = `(↑u : K) * (↑v : K)⁻¹`, because `(↑(v⁻¹ : (O K)ˣ) : K)` is `(v : K)⁻¹`.\n\nThus, `(↑(u / v) : K)` is `(u : K) / (v : K)`.\n\nNow, we check the `hu : IsUnit u✝` part. It is irrelevant if we know that",
